items.title: Thank you for participating in this important research!
items.content:
Press Space to download a CSV file with the data. In the CSV file, the audio is encoded as Base64 strings in the 'audio' column. Base64 can be converted to an audio file using a Python/R/JavaScript script or a website such as base64.guru.

Note: The string cannot be directly decoded as Base64 without first removing the Data-URL declaration preceding the Base64-encoded data. That is, remove the following part from the string: data:audio/ogg; codecs=opus;base64,

Once extracted, the filetype of the audio is `.ogg`. Not all media players can play ogg files. ​VLC is a good free audio player that can.

If you are running this study on JATOS, the data will be stored on JATOS, too. You can find more information in the lab.js docs.

items.title: Audio recorder test
items.content:
Use the record button below to test if the recording works, 
then press the <kbd>Space</kbd> key to continue.

metadata.title: labjs audio recording demo
metadata.description:
On each trial the participant names a cat. Audio is recorded from their microphone.
There's one trial with a record button (optional, the recorded clip can be shown on the page) and a trial without a record button that starts automatically and ends when the user presses a key (automatically progressing to the next trial).
